==Post-war life==
Kayser left the military after the war, and spent the rest of his professional career working in the private business sector. He was a member of [[Fana]] [[municipal council (Norway)|municipal council]] for eight years during the 1950s, representing the [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]], although he was not formally a member of the party.<ref name=ntb>{{cite news|title=Fredrik Kayser 80 <U+00E5>r 25. mai|agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]]|date=20 May 1998|language=Norwegian}}</ref> He also became a devout Christian after the war.<ref name=bt93/>

Kayser played himself in the [[docudrama]] ''[[The Fight Over the Heavy Water|Kampen om tungtvannet]]'', released in 1948. Despite appearing publicly in the film, for several decades Kayser was unwilling to conduct in-depth interviews about his wartime actions.<ref name=bt-obit>{{cite news|url=http://www.bt.no/lokalt/bergen/article785254.ece|title=Krigshelten d<U+00F8>de mandag|last=Lura|first=Christian|date=2 February 2009|work=Bergens Tidende|language=Norwegian|accessdate=4 February 2009}}</ref> He cited recurring nightmares as the reason for his unwillingness to recapitulate the war period.<ref name=aft/> Ultimately, the writer Kjell Harald Lunde got Kayser's consent, and in 1997 Lunde published the book ''Sabot<U+00F8>ren'' ('The Saboteur').<ref name=bt-obit/> Kayser had participated in a [[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] production on ''Bj<U+00F8>rn West'' in the spring of 1994. Kayser's son, Johan Fr. Kayser, played his father in the television production.<ref name="Bj<U+00F8>rnW"/>

Fredrik Kayser died on 2 February 2009, having suffered from failing health for four months.<ref name=bt-obit/> He had lived in [[<U+00C5>gotnes]] since 1974.<ref name=ntb/>

